  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Addressing Urgent Humanitarian Needs of Internally Displaced Persons and Returnees in Iraq</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The humanitarian context in Iraq has evolved in the past years following the official end of the Islamic State in the Levant (ISIL) crisis in December 2017. The post-conflict period has seen the gradual return of over 4.8 million people to their areas of origin. Since then, Iraq has been facing multiple overlapping crises resulting from the years of violent conflict, which have led to protracted displacement. The COVID-19 pandemic and its associated public health, socio-economic and mobility impacts have amplified these issues, often acting as a threat multiplier in Iraq&#x2019;s fragile context. Through this project, IOM is providing needed humanitarian assistance in formal camps and informal sites through camp coordination and camp management, shelter, non-food items, cash-based assistance, mental health and psychosocial support, protection case management and provision of essential health care services to internally displaced persons.</narrative>
  </description>
